s repository is intentionally not a visual reskin of the existing public resource. It demonstrates a new product architecture in which public legal authority, property-specific applicability, accountable remediation, executive decisions, and response evidence operate on one governed record.
+
+## Product thesis
+
+A material legal change should be able to move through the enterprise without being reconstructed at every handoff:
+
+```text
+Source → Rule → Change → Applicability → Matter → Finding
+       → Control → Evidence → Decision → Revalidation
+```
+
+The public site supplies readable, citable authority. The private control plane resolves that authority against portfolio facts and carries the result through ownership, implementation, assurance, and approval.
+
+The interface is therefore organized around the enterprise's actual objects—not around four conceptual “modes”:
+
+- **Changes** — verified developments and portfolio reach
+- **Matters** — governed response records
+- **Controls** — obligations converted into operating proof
+- **Portfolio** — property and workforce applicability
+- **Research** — grounded answers with source lineage
+- **Decision records** — concise, approved executive artifacts
+
+## What is included
+
+### Public authority layer
+
+| Route | Purpose |
+|---|---|
+| `/` | Category-defining platform narrative and causal system model |
+| `/intelligence/` | Developments, issue architecture, tools, and corpus overview |
+| `/jurisdictions/` | 50-state + D.C. complexity explorer and comparison standard |
+| `/tools/` | Inspectable workflow registry and example audit anatomy |
+| `/methodology/` | Evidence, governance, source, privacy, and calculation standards |
+
+### Enterprise control plane
+
+| Route | Purpose |
+|---|---|
+| `/app/` | Portfolio command view and decision queue |
+| `/app/changes/` | Change-to-response impact analysis |
+| `/app/matters/la-hotel-wage-2026/` | Governed matter with scenario modeling, findings, and evidence |
+| `/app/controls/` | Control coverage, exceptions, testing, and assurance |
+| `/app/research/` | Source-grounded legal research workspace |
+| `/app/briefs/la-hotel-wage-2026/` | Versioned executive decision record |
+| `/app/properties/dtla-01/` | Property passport and applicable-obligation model |
+
+All enterprise names, people, financial ranges, scores, work states, and portfolio values are illustrative prototype data.
+
+## Run locally
+
+Requirements:
+
+- Node.js 20 or later
+- Python 3.11 or later for browser QA and rendering
+- Chromium and Python Playwright for browser QA
+
+```bash
+npm run build
+npm run serve
+```
+
+Open `http://localhost:8080`.
+
+## Validate
+
+```bash
+npm test          # deterministic build + structural/data tests
+npm run qa        # browser, responsive, and interaction acceptance tests
+npm run verify    # both suites
+```
+
+The test suite validates:
+
+- all 12 routes and internal references
+- corpus and jurisdiction dimensions
+- object-graph and evidence-contract semantics
+- explicit prototype/legal limitations
+- no fabricated customer proof
+- desktop and mobile overflow
+- browser-console errors
+- command/search, source drawer, filters, scenario model, control drawer, approvals, and mobile navigation
+
+## Build for GitHub Pages
+
+```bash
+npm run check:pages
+```
+
+This builds with the `/hotel-wage-law-v2` prefix and validates route, asset, robots, and web-manifest paths. The included Pages workflow performs the verified build and deploys the generated `docs/` directory as an artifact; generated output is not versioned.
+
+## Production boundary
+
+This is a high-fidelity front-end prototype and system specification. It is **not** a production legal application and does not provide legal advice. A production release requires, among other things:
+
+- a canonical legal-content and source-version service
+- a validated applicability and calculation engine
+- property, workforce, payroll, benefit, and policy integrations
+- authentication, tenant isolation, privilege controls, and audit logging
+- workflow persistence, evidence storage, approvals, notifications, and legal holds
+- attorney review of legal logic and editorial governance
+- security, privacy, accessibility, resilience, observability, and performance programs
+
+See [`product/`](product/) for the product thesis, experience and production architecture, visual and content systems, governed data schema, analytics, governance, security, migration plan, roadmap, and acceptance criteria.
+
+## Repository governance
+
+The implementation has no runtime package dependencies and produces deterministic static output suitable for review, design handoff, and architectural validation. Continuous integration, review-only Pages deployment, code ownership, structured issue intake, dependency monitoring, security guidance, and a governed pull-request checklist are included.
+
+The private reference implementation was accessed through the authenticated GitHub connector for repository reconnaissance. Its data-driven legal corpus, calculators, tests, generated output, and verification research are treated as migration inputs—not as material to overwrite or casually copy. See [`product/REPO-AUDIT.md`](product/REPO-AUDIT.md) and [`product/MIGRATION.md`](product/MIGRATION.md).
+
+See [`GITHUB-OPERATIONS.md`](GITHUB-OPERATIONS.md) for repository controls and the deployment boundary.
+The ordered implementation backlog is maintained in [`product/GITHUB-BACKLOG.md`](product/GITHUB-BACKLOG.md) and should be mirrored into GitHub issues.
+
+## License
+
+All rights reserved. See [`LICENSE`](LICENSE).
